Think carefully about how to design a quality analysis system that remains useful and accurate as a codebase scales from 10,000 lines to 10,000,000 lines. At small scale, a tool can afford to be thorough and slow. At large scale, the same analysis must complete in a bounded time window or it cannot be used in CI. But the transition between these regimes is not a step function — teams gradually grow their codebases and do not want to switch to a different tool configuration at an arbitrary threshold.

Reason through the following scaling challenges. First, the full-scan versus incremental analysis trade-off: at what codebase size does a full scan become impractical in a CI context (assuming 2-minute budget), and what is the right incremental analysis strategy at each scale tier? Consider that incremental analysis requires a content-addressable cache and an invalidation strategy, which adds engineering complexity and potential for stale results. Second, the duplication detection scaling problem: token-based duplication detection is O(n^2) in the naive case. What are the algorithmic approaches that bring this to O(n log n) or O(n) — suffix arrays, LSH (locality sensitive hashing), inverted token indexes — and what is their implementation complexity and approximate constant factors? Third, the parallel analysis architecture: most file-level analyses are embarrassingly parallel, but aggregation steps (computing project-wide metrics, deduplication of clone pairs across files) require coordination. Design a parallel pipeline architecture that maximizes CPU utilization on an 8-core CI worker for a 500,000 line Python codebase, specifying which stages are map steps and which are reduce steps. Fourth, the reporting problem: a 10 million line codebase might have 50,000 quality violations. A report containing all of them is useless. How should the system prioritize, sample, or summarize findings at scale while ensuring that the highest-severity issues in the most frequently-changed files always surface?
